item.description:
1. What is tidyverse and why would you use it?  tidyverse is a collection of R packages that make working on data a much nicer experience than using base R;
 it consists of tidyr, dplyr, ggplot2, tibble and a few more.
  To be honest, I prefer data.table to tidyverse, as it resembles basic R data.frames, is faster, more concise and, IMHO, more SQL-ish. But it takes longer to master and may be more difficult to understand, even your own code after some time.

1. What is data.table and why would you use it?  data.table is an R packge which let’s you work on tabular datasets quickly and easily;
 comparing to base R or dplyr it’s significantly faster;
 data.table has a concise and SQL-like syntax.
   2. Basic functionalities Creating a data.table library(data.table) df &lt;- data.frame(x = c(&quot;b&quot;,&quot;b&quot;,&quot;b&quot;,&quot;a&quot;,&quot;a&quot;), v = rnorm(5)) dt &lt;- data.table(x = c(&quot;b&quot;,&quot;b&quot;,&quot;b&quot;,&quot;a&quot;,&quot;a&quot;), v = rnorm(5)) is exactly the same as creating a data.
